'''John George Adami''' (ä-dä' mee), M.A., M.D., [[List of Fellows of the Royal Society A,B,C|F.R.S.]], LL.D. (12 January 1862 [[Manchester]] - 29 August 1926 [[Liverpool]]) was a British [[pathologist]].

He was the son of the late John George Adami. He was educated at [[Owen College]], Manchester, and at [[Christ's College, Cambridge]],<ref>{{Venn|id=ADMY880JG|name=Adami, John George}}</ref> studying afterward in Breslau and Paris. 
He took distinguished honors at Cambridge in natural science, was Darwin prizeman in 1885, M.R.C.S., and was appointed demonstrator of pathology in [[Cambridge University]] in 1887. 
In 1888, he exposed himself to rabies, and published an account of his treatment at the [[Pasteur Institute]]'s vaccination clinic. <ref>http://www.educationengland.org.uk/articles/24hadow.html</ref>
Elected fellow of [[Jesus College, Cambridge]], in 1891, he soon after became head of the pathological department of the [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Montreal|Royal Victoria Hospital]]. <ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=lDBXAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA301&dq=John+George+Adami&as_brr=3&cd=3#v=onepage&q=John%20George%20Adami&f=false ''Montreal, 1535-1914''], William Henry Atherton, S. J. Clarke, 1914</ref>
From 1892, he was professor of pathology in [[McGill University]], Canada. <ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=oFpmAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA1&lpg=PA1&dq=John+George+Adami&source=bl&ots=62ijJIfEq1&sig=6wdlnuQkj77l8bZLQA7YyAatxjs&hl=en&ei=eaboS8S9LcKAlAf9qfXGAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CCgQ6AEwBTgK#v=onepage&q=John%20George%20Adami&f=false ''The Canadian who's who''], Volume 1, University of Toronto Press, 1910</ref>
During [[World War I]], he inspected Canadian hospitals in France. 
From 1919, he was Vice-Chancellor of [[University of Liverpool]].<ref>[http://www.jstor.org/pss/94636 "Address of the President"], November 30, 1926, Ernest Rutherford, ''Proceedings of the Royal Society of London''. Series A, Vol. 113, No. 765 (Jan. 1, 1927), pp. 481-495</ref>

He is the author of numerous monographs upon subjects relating to pathology in French, German, English and American medical journals, and of many papers read before medical societies.
He was elected [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] on 11 May 1905.

In 1894, he married Mary Stuart, she remarried.
His wartime diary is held at the Welcome Library.<ref>http://library.wellcome.ac.uk/doc_WTL039911.html</ref>
The Adami Lectureship in Pathology is given by University of Liverpool.<ref>http://www.liv.ac.uk/commsec/calendar_07_08/special_lectureships.htm</ref>

